for gayodaAqiI-N↓]: (TA:) and it is said that gayodaAqN applied to a boy signifies that has not attained to puberty. (TA.)

gadiI-N 
Of, or relating to, the morrow; the rel. n. from gadN; 
as also gadawI-N↓; (Ṣ, Ḳ;) the latter allowable. (Ṣ.)

hom.sense:
And ‡ Generous; open, or fair, or illustrious, in his actions; (Ḳ;) applied to a man: (TA:) eminent; noble; 
as also gurogurapN↓: (Ṣ, Ḳ:) or fair-faced: or a lord, or chief, among his people: (Mṣb:) pl. gur-N, (T, M,) accord. to the Ḳ gurarN, but the former is more correct, (TA,) and gur-aAnN. (T, M, Ḳ.) 
And gur-aI↓ signifies † A woman of rank, eminence, or nobility, among her tribe. (Ṣgh, Ḳ, TA.)

4. UigoraAbN signifies The going far into a land, or country; 
as also tagoriybN↓. (Ḳ.) 
And you say, gr-bt↓ AlkilaAbu The dogs went far in search, or pursuit, of the object, or objects, of the chase. (A, TA.)

