entry.sense:
gariyzapN 
Nature: or natural, native, innate, or original, disposition, temper, or other quality or property; idiosynerasy; 
[of the measure faEiylapN in the sense of the measure mafoEuwlapN; as though signifying a disposition,, &c., implanted by the Creator;] syn. TabiyEapN, (Lḥ, Ṣ, Mṣb, Ḳ,) and qariyHapN, (Ṣ,) and sajiy-apN, (TA.) and OaSolN; (Lḥ, TA;) whether good or bad; as, for instance, courage, and cowardice: pl. garaAYizu. (TA.)

migorafN; 
and the pl. magaArifu: 
see the next preceding paragraph, first sentence.

gaAriyquwnN, (Mgh, Ḳ,) or OagaAriyquwnN, (Ḳ,) an ancient Greek word, 
[ἀγαρικὸν,] (TA,) A certain medicine; a thing [or substance] resembling OanojucaAn; 
[see HilotiytN;] male and female; in the bitterness of which is a sweetness: (Mgh:) or the root, or stem, (OaSol,) of a certain plant: or a certain thing [or substance] which originates in worm-eaten trees; an antidote to poisons, (Ḳ, TA,) an attenuant of turbid humour, exhilarant, (Ḳ,* TA,) and good for sciatica; and [it is said that] he upon whom it is suspended will not be stung by a scorpion. (Ḳ, TA.)

